497
00:20:08,479 --> 00:20:10,246
but we should discuss it.

498
00:20:10,281 --> 00:20:12,432
(Lowered voice) Election rigging
is not an option.

499
00:20:12,966 --> 00:20:15,851
(Lowered voice) I'm talking
about doing a patriotic thing.

500
00:20:15,886 --> 00:20:17,486
You're not serious.

501
00:20:17,521 --> 00:20:19,055
I may be a son of a bitch,
but Fitz is clean as a whistle.

502
00:20:19,089 --> 00:20:20,156
Am I right, Cyrus?

503
00:20:24,460 --> 00:20:25,944
He's the real deal.

504
00:20:25,978 --> 00:20:28,597
A patriot.
A believer.

505
00:20:28,631 --> 00:20:31,316
How rare is that?
How often does that come along?

506
00:20:31,351 --> 00:20:33,585
Once in a generation,
if you're lucky.

507
00:20:33,636 --> 00:20:35,404
I'm just saying,
this is our chance

508
00:20:35,438 --> 00:20:38,757
to put a man with integrity
inside that big white house.

509
00:20:38,808 --> 00:20:42,811
So you want to do this
because Fitz is so good? Really?

510
00:20:42,845 --> 00:20:46,114
Doesn't matter why I want to do it.

511
00:20:46,449 --> 00:20:48,016
It matters why you'd want to.

512
00:20:50,403 --> 00:20:51,870
What are we talking about?

513
00:20:52,905 --> 00:20:55,206
(Normal voice) Nothing.

514
00:20:55,241 --> 00:20:57,709
(Normal voice)
Pull up a chair, Mellie.

515
00:20:57,743 --> 00:20:59,094
Let's have a discussion.

516
00:21:09,447 --> 00:21:10,814
Fitz is out on his feet.
He's weak,

517
00:21:10,849 --> 00:21:12,516
has trouble concentrating,
plain as day.

518
00:21:12,567 --> 00:21:14,234
Presiding over a national
security crisis...

519
00:21:14,269 --> 00:21:15,652
It's damn near treason.

520
00:21:15,703 --> 00:21:17,988
- He's nixed the air strikes.
- Ooh. He's what?

521
00:21:18,422 --> 00:21:19,739
Do I bring him
before congress,

522
00:21:19,774 --> 00:21:21,525
expose his unfitness
to the American people?

523
00:21:21,559 --> 00:21:23,426
No. No.
You do nothing.

524
00:21:23,461 --> 00:21:25,295
Just let him hang himself
with his own lasso.

525
00:21:25,329 --> 00:21:26,763
Mulish pridefulness
about provin' himself

526
00:21:26,797 --> 00:21:28,181
has always been
that boy's Achilles' heel

527
00:21:28,216 --> 00:21:29,633
goin' back to him
and his daddy.

528
00:21:29,667 --> 00:21:31,051
All you got to do
is lay back, be set,

529
00:21:31,085 --> 00:21:33,620
step in once he crashes
and burns.

530
00:21:34,438 --> 00:21:36,072
Your dad is helping.

531
00:21:36,123 --> 00:21:38,207
The numbers are giving you
good news.

532
00:21:38,241 --> 00:21:39,792
- Although...
- Although?

533
00:21:41,111 --> 00:21:43,312
You're still 7 points down
overall.

534
00:21:43,347 --> 00:21:45,748
(Groans)

535
00:21:47,567 --> 00:21:48,634
Come on!

536
00:21:49,169 --> 00:21:51,436
How was this not fixed earlier?
You!

537
00:21:51,454 --> 00:21:53,021
You have done this before, right?

538
00:21:53,056 --> 00:21:54,957
This is not your first time
plugging in a microphone?

539
00:21:54,991 --> 00:21:57,960
We did hire someone who knows
how to do this job, right?!

540
00:21:57,994 --> 00:22:00,028
Governor.
That's Jason.

541
00:22:00,063 --> 00:22:01,930
And he's almost done fixing
the sound system.

542
00:22:01,965 --> 00:22:03,932
- He just needs a minute.
- This is a town hall forum.

543
00:22:03,967 --> 00:22:05,751
You got people spread
all around the room,

544
00:22:05,785 --> 00:22:07,953
and I cannot hear
what they are saying!

545
00:22:07,971 --> 00:22:11,288
What's the point of a debate
prep if I can't debate?

546
00:22:11,306 --> 00:22:13,541
Everyone, good work.
But let's call it a night.

547
00:22:13,576 --> 00:22:14,726
(Sighs)
Go home, get some sleep.

548
00:22:14,760 --> 00:22:16,744
We'll start here again
at 7:00 A.M.

549
00:22:18,179 --> 00:22:19,581
Not you.

550
00:22:20,716 --> 00:22:23,334
Those people are working
their butts off for you.

551
00:22:23,368 --> 00:22:25,302
- Then we need better people.
- Or we need a better candidate.

552
00:22:25,320 --> 00:22:26,437
Screw you.

553
00:22:26,471 --> 00:22:28,322
I am getting killed
in these debates.

554
00:22:28,373 --> 00:22:30,608
I lose votes in these debates.
I need to be prepared.

555
00:22:30,642 --> 00:22:32,794
Which is what we were doing when
you started yelling at people.

556
00:22:32,845 --> 00:22:34,378
I am yelling because no
one is doing their job.

557
00:22:34,413 --> 00:22:36,531
- Your job is to make sure I win.
- Good.

558
00:22:37,465 --> 00:22:40,667
I was worried you thought
my job is to get felt up

559
00:22:40,701 --> 00:22:42,218
in elevators
by my drunken candidate.

560
00:22:42,253 --> 00:22:43,703
I'm sorry about that.
You know I'm sorry about that.

561
00:22:43,738 --> 00:22:45,572
- Do you even want this?
- What?

562
00:22:45,623 --> 00:22:47,290
Do you even want
to be President?

563
00:22:47,325 --> 00:22:48,692
Obviously.

564
00:22:48,726 --> 00:22:50,660
Is it obvious?
I'm running.

565
00:22:50,678 --> 00:22:52,529
You're running like
you're being chased.

566
00:22:52,563 --> 00:22:54,264
You're not running like you want
to cross the finish line first,

567
00:22:54,399 --> 00:22:56,933
and so I'm asking you,
do you want it?

568
00:22:56,967 --> 00:22:59,786
Or are you just wasting
everyone's time

569
00:22:59,820 --> 00:23:03,406
and money and energy and
faith and hopes and dreams?!

570
00:23:03,441 --> 00:23:04,808
- I want it.
- Why?

571
00:23:04,842 --> 00:23:06,176
- Liv. - Why do you want
to be the President?

572
00:23:06,210 --> 00:23:07,344
Okay, Olivia.
Why?!

573
00:23:07,378 --> 00:23:08,928
I don't know what you
want me to say!

574
00:23:08,963 --> 00:23:11,681
That's your problem.
You're always trying to say

575
00:23:11,716 --> 00:23:12,949
what you think
everyone wants to hear,

576
00:23:12,983 --> 00:23:14,584
be what you think everyone
wants you to be,

577
00:23:14,602 --> 00:23:15,885
and I should have caught it before.

578
00:23:15,919 --> 00:23:18,788
I would have if we weren't...
(Sighs)

579
00:23:20,825 --> 00:23:23,426
I know you...

580
00:23:24,361 --> 00:23:26,161
Because you let me know you.

581
00:23:26,196 --> 00:23:28,631
But America has no idea
who you are,

582
00:23:28,665 --> 00:23:31,800
because you've never let them
know who you are.

583
00:23:31,835 --> 00:23:33,302
Nobody can tell you
how to do that.

584
00:23:33,336 --> 00:23:35,604
I can't fix that, because
I'm not running for President.

585
00:23:35,638 --> 00:23:37,439
Neither is Cyrus,
neither is your father,

586
00:23:37,457 --> 00:23:38,757
so who are <i>you,</i>

587
00:23:38,792 --> 00:23:42,494
and why do <i>you</i>
want to be President?

588
00:23:42,529 --> 00:23:44,680
Mellie came to me.
I tried to stop it, but...

589
00:23:44,714 --> 00:23:46,682
(Sighs) He's Fitz.

590
00:23:46,716 --> 00:23:49,051
He'll look okay on tv, but...

591
00:23:49,069 --> 00:23:51,320
- What? - The man is supposed
to be in the hospital,

592
00:23:51,354 --> 00:23:54,189
and instead he's been
working all day.

593
00:23:55,659 --> 00:23:57,176
(Lowered voice) I don't think
he'll last on his feet

594
00:23:57,210 --> 00:23:59,578
more than 30 seconds.
You have to shut this down.

595
00:23:59,612 --> 00:24:04,917
(Indistinct conversations)

596
00:24:04,951 --> 00:24:06,819
(Door closes)

597
00:24:07,870 --> 00:24:09,921
I hear someone
is being stubborn.

598
00:24:09,955 --> 00:24:11,439
Cyrus sent you.

599
00:24:11,457 --> 00:24:13,358
It might not be wise to
answer questions on live tv

600
00:24:13,392 --> 00:24:14,976
in your condition.

601
00:24:15,010 --> 00:24:17,045
It might not be wise,
but that's what I'm gonna do.

602
00:24:17,079 --> 00:24:19,764
Mind telling me why?

603
00:24:19,798 --> 00:24:22,033
What you said.

604
00:24:22,067 --> 00:24:23,651
I'm stubborn.

605
00:24:28,273 --> 00:24:29,974
(Exhales)

606
00:24:31,510 --> 00:24:33,811
(Exhales and chuckles)

607
00:24:35,464 --> 00:24:36,748
(Exhales)

608
00:24:38,966 --> 00:24:40,884
- You almost died.
- Yes.

609
00:24:40,918 --> 00:24:43,019
- Don't do it again.
- Okay.

610
00:24:48,426 --> 00:24:50,227
(Kisses)

611
00:24:50,261 --> 00:24:52,379
(Sighs)

612
00:24:52,413 --> 00:24:54,080
You can't do
this press conference.

613
00:24:54,114 --> 00:24:56,733
You're not strong enough...
Not yet.

614
00:24:56,767 --> 00:24:58,985
I'm doing the press conference.

615
00:24:59,020 --> 00:25:02,405
Tell me why. Tell me why
it's so important to you.

616
00:25:02,457 --> 00:25:03,857
(Groans softly)

617
00:25:06,344 --> 00:25:09,312
This is <i>my</i> office.

618
00:25:09,347 --> 00:25:11,214
I'm the President.

619
00:25:12,149 --> 00:25:14,100
They can shoot me
if they want to,

620
00:25:14,134 --> 00:25:15,868
but I'm not going anywhere,
because the people

621
00:25:15,902 --> 00:25:17,386
of this country elected
me to this office,

622
00:25:17,421 --> 00:25:20,256
and the people deserve to see me
and to know that I'm in charge.

623
00:25:20,290 --> 00:25:22,324
(Knock on door)

624
00:25:22,359 --> 00:25:26,929
(Door opens and closes)

625
00:25:28,098 --> 00:25:29,265
Well?

626
00:25:29,299 --> 00:25:32,084
He's doing the press conference...

627
00:25:32,102 --> 00:25:33,469
Live.

628
00:25:33,520 --> 00:25:36,372
And he's going to take
questions.

629
00:25:36,406 --> 00:25:38,424
And it's gonna be great.

630
00:25:38,442 --> 00:25:40,826
And it's gonna be great.

631
00:25:40,860 --> 00:25:42,261
(Exhales)

632
00:25:48,247 --> 00:25:50,964
Reston's narrative is that
he was an angry young man

633
00:25:51,015 --> 00:25:53,333
until meeting his wife Joan,
who turned him into

634
00:25:53,368 --> 00:25:55,268
the upstanding
public servant he is today.

635
00:25:55,302 --> 00:25:58,038
Turns out it wasn't love
that fixed him.

636
00:25:58,089 --> 00:25:59,956
- It was Prozac.
- Hmm.

637
00:25:59,990 --> 00:26:01,457
(Projector and camera shutter clicks)

638
00:26:01,491 --> 00:26:03,209
- But this isn't Reston's.
- We pulled it from his trash.

639
00:26:03,243 --> 00:26:05,328
His doctors hide it
under a bunch of fake names,

640
00:26:05,362 --> 00:26:07,329
but they all lead back
to Samuel Montrose Reston.

641
00:26:07,347 --> 00:26:09,398
Fluoxetine.
60 milligrams a day.

642
00:26:09,432 --> 00:26:11,784
For the past 20 years.
That's a pretty heavy habit.

643
00:26:11,835 --> 00:26:14,437
My suggestion, if we choose
to go forward with this,

644
00:26:14,471 --> 00:26:16,455
is to leak rumors
of prescription drug abuse

645
00:26:16,507 --> 00:26:17,907
to the press
before the final debate.

646
00:26:17,941 --> 00:26:19,492
It will take over
the news cycle

647
00:26:19,526 --> 00:26:21,410
and prevent Reston from
being able to prepare properly.

648
00:26:22,145 --> 00:26:23,545
That's a fine suggestion, honey,

649
00:26:23,580 --> 00:26:25,547
but that's not what
we're gonna do.

650
00:26:25,582 --> 00:26:28,133
We're gonna sit on it
until the debate itself.

651
00:26:28,167 --> 00:26:30,085
And then you're gonna work it
into one of your answers

652
00:26:30,119 --> 00:26:32,754
and blindside Reston
and send him up a creek

653
00:26:32,788 --> 00:26:35,641
without a paddle
and demolish him in the process.

654
00:26:35,675 --> 00:26:38,176
(Olivia) - Ahh.
(Jerry chuckles) - Huh?

655
00:26:38,928 --> 00:26:40,895
If you need a rest or don't
know the answer to a question,

656
00:26:40,930 --> 00:26:43,181
take a sip of water.
This is a press conference.

657
00:26:43,215 --> 00:26:44,916
This is a town hall-style debate...

658
00:26:44,950 --> 00:26:46,284
Real Americans
with real questions

659
00:26:46,318 --> 00:26:47,952
looking to you for real answers.
Put them...

660
00:26:48,003 --> 00:26:50,655
at ease. This isn't about
military strategy.

661
00:26:50,706 --> 00:26:51,906
It's about convincing
the American people

662
00:26:51,941 --> 00:26:54,258
that their commander-in-chief
is not just back,

663
00:26:54,293 --> 00:26:56,293
but up to the job.

664
00:26:56,328 --> 00:26:58,028
So I wait for a question
about the military?

665
00:26:58,062 --> 00:26:59,546
That's when you drop the bomb.

666
00:26:59,581 --> 00:27:00,948
Give them a choice
between a candidate

667
00:27:00,982 --> 00:27:02,349
who's flown combat missions

668
00:27:02,383 --> 00:27:03,884
and a candidate who takes
antidepressants.

669
00:27:03,902 --> 00:27:06,870
Got it?
Got it?

670
00:27:06,905 --> 00:27:07,988
Fitz?

671
00:27:08,006 --> 00:27:09,239
I got it.

672
00:27:09,274 --> 00:27:10,774
Good.

673
00:27:11,843 --> 00:27:14,710
Now show them who you are.

674
00:27:15,129 --> 00:27:17,965
(Indistinct conversations)

675
00:27:20,969 --> 00:27:23,904
(Applause)

676
00:27:31,396 --> 00:27:33,030
(Camera shutters clicking)

677
00:27:33,064 --> 00:27:36,116
At 5:00 this evening
eastern standard time,

678
00:27:36,150 --> 00:27:40,270
a U.S. Navy S.E.A.L.team
parachuted into east Sudan

679
00:27:40,305 --> 00:27:44,640
and captured its President,
Nijam Kinyazi.

680
00:27:44,874 --> 00:27:46,325
(Reston)
The Governor's posturing, Carl.

681
00:27:46,359 --> 00:27:47,659
He wants you to believe
that he's trustworthy,

682
00:27:47,694 --> 00:27:49,011
that he's his father.

683
00:27:49,045 --> 00:27:51,113
He's not his father.
His father was a self-made man.

684
00:27:51,147 --> 00:27:52,798
The Governor...
he was made

685
00:27:52,832 --> 00:27:54,633
on a boarding school assembly line.

686
00:27:54,667 --> 00:27:56,218
He can't relate to you.
(Camera shutter clicks)

687
00:27:56,252 --> 00:27:57,903
(Reporters shouting questions)
(Under breath) Here we go.

688
00:27:57,921 --> 00:27:59,605
- Yes, Carol?
- What were the casualties?

689
00:27:59,639 --> 00:28:02,657
- None on our side.
- And theirs?

690
00:28:02,691 --> 00:28:03,592
I don't have numbers
for you yet,

691
00:28:03,626 --> 00:28:05,444
but I'm told there were
several, all non-civilian.

692
00:28:06,778 --> 00:28:08,179
(Reporters shouting questions)
Yeah. Peter?

693
00:28:08,213 --> 00:28:11,014
Having just survived
an assassination attempt,

694
00:28:11,032 --> 00:28:12,750
is there any concern
about P.T.S.D.

695
00:28:12,784 --> 00:28:16,437
or impaired brain functioning that
<i>could</i> affect your judgment?

696
00:28:16,471 --> 00:28:21,542
(Shutters clicking)

697
00:28:21,576 --> 00:28:23,978
(Reporters murmuring)

698
00:28:24,012 --> 00:28:25,980
Oh, boy.

699
00:28:27,849 --> 00:28:29,533
(Clicking continues)

700
00:28:30,584 --> 00:28:33,436
(Moderator) The next question
is for Governor Grant,

701
00:28:33,454 --> 00:28:35,504
and it's from Jessica Moran.

702
00:28:35,523 --> 00:28:37,240
- Jessica.
- Governor Grant...

703
00:28:37,274 --> 00:28:38,291
Hi, Jessica.

704
00:28:38,325 --> 00:28:40,210
As the mother
of an 18-year-old boy

705
00:28:40,244 --> 00:28:43,079
who's about to enlist
in the army,

706
00:28:43,113 --> 00:28:46,249
why should I trust you
as our next commander-in-chief?

707
00:28:46,283 --> 00:28:47,784
(Under breath) This is it.

708
00:28:47,818 --> 00:28:49,702
You know, people talk
about a lack of patriotism

709
00:28:49,753 --> 00:28:51,221
in our country.

710
00:28:52,255 --> 00:28:53,856
They're wrong.

711
00:28:53,890 --> 00:28:56,308
And your son is proof of that.

712
00:28:56,342 --> 00:28:59,244
Now, as for whether
you should trust me

713
00:28:59,279 --> 00:29:00,963
as commander-in-chief...

714
00:29:00,997 --> 00:29:02,297
Say it.

715
00:29:02,331 --> 00:29:04,666
(Chuckles)

716
00:29:04,701 --> 00:29:06,668
What I should say

717
00:29:06,686 --> 00:29:09,121
is that I've served
in the military,

718
00:29:09,155 --> 00:29:11,806
and I've flown combat missions,

719
00:29:11,824 --> 00:29:13,659
and the courage that I exhibited

720
00:29:13,693 --> 00:29:15,677
makes me fit
to lead this country.

721
00:29:15,712 --> 00:29:17,763
That's what I should say,

722
00:29:17,797 --> 00:29:20,649
because my pollsters
and aides and advisors

723
00:29:20,683 --> 00:29:22,334
tell me that's what you
want to hear.

724
00:29:22,368 --> 00:29:23,752
What the hell's he doing?

725
00:29:23,786 --> 00:29:25,737
But the truth is, Jessica...

726
00:29:25,772 --> 00:29:28,924
Those years I spent
in the Navy...

727
00:29:28,958 --> 00:29:30,909
It wasn't courage I felt.

728
00:29:31,744 --> 00:29:34,062
It was fear.

729
00:29:34,096 --> 00:29:35,880
Fear that I'd crash.

730
00:29:35,914 --> 00:29:39,317
Fear that the life
that I wanted to live

731
00:29:39,368 --> 00:29:43,337
would end in a ball of flames
a million Miles from home.

732
00:29:43,372 --> 00:29:47,175
It literally made me sick.

733
00:29:47,209 --> 00:29:50,745
Now does that mean
that I am not fit

734
00:29:50,779 --> 00:29:53,715
to be commander-in-chief?

735
00:29:53,949 --> 00:29:55,383
(Camera shutter clicks)

736
00:29:55,417 --> 00:29:56,584
(Projector clicks)

737
00:29:56,618 --> 00:29:59,504
(Camera shutters clicking)

738
00:30:00,938 --> 00:30:02,105
No.

739
00:30:03,958 --> 00:30:05,758
In fact, I've never felt
more ready.

740
00:30:05,793 --> 00:30:07,594
Weakness is our strength.

741
00:30:07,628 --> 00:30:08,878
(Camera shutters clicking)

742
00:30:08,913 --> 00:30:11,664
It's what makes us human.

743
00:30:11,999 --> 00:30:14,867
- It's where our compassion
comes from. - I don't believe this.

744
00:30:14,902 --> 00:30:16,402
Our humility.

745
00:30:16,437 --> 00:30:19,705
All qualities that make for
a great commander-in-chief.

746
00:30:19,740 --> 00:30:22,809
You can't have someone
protect you

747
00:30:22,843 --> 00:30:25,210
if they don't know
what you're afraid of.

748
00:30:25,244 --> 00:30:27,646
I know what you're afraid of.

749
00:30:27,664 --> 00:30:29,982
I know what
your son's afraid of.

750
00:30:30,017 --> 00:30:31,901
Why?

751
00:30:31,935 --> 00:30:33,986
Because I'm afraid of it, too.

752
00:30:34,021 --> 00:30:35,721
(Applause)

753
00:30:35,756 --> 00:30:36,973
(Jessica) Thank you.

754
00:30:39,424 --> 00:30:40,659
Works for me.

755
00:30:40,693 --> 00:30:43,328
- Grant the protector.
- Yeah.

756
00:30:43,363 --> 00:30:46,164
Pull the file on Reston's stint
as Baltimore D.A.

757
00:30:46,182 --> 00:30:48,283
- We're painting him as soft on crime.
- Yeah.

758
00:30:48,334 --> 00:30:50,736
(Applause,
camera shutters clicking)

759
00:30:50,754 --> 00:30:52,938
(Fitz) Good night.

760
00:30:58,894 --> 00:31:01,011
You knocked it
out of the park, sir.

761
00:31:01,045 --> 00:31:02,680
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

762
00:31:02,714 --> 00:31:04,665
(Laughs)

763
00:31:04,699 --> 00:31:06,934
So that's how you're gonna
win this thing, huh?

764
00:31:06,968 --> 00:31:09,320
By taking out a hankie
and crying?

765
00:31:09,354 --> 00:31:12,056
She teed it up for you
and you whiffed.

766
00:31:12,090 --> 00:31:13,757
(Scoffs)

767
00:31:13,792 --> 00:31:17,912
I know that I've won
fewer elections than you.

768
00:31:17,946 --> 00:31:19,530
But not because you were
better than me,

769
00:31:19,548 --> 00:31:20,998
because you are not.

770
00:31:21,016 --> 00:31:22,933
You are a petty man.
You are an underhanded man.

771
00:31:22,967 --> 00:31:25,669
You are a small man,
and I don't want to be you,

772
00:31:25,704 --> 00:31:27,938
not now, not ever.

773
00:31:28,006 --> 00:31:29,640
You're gonna lose
this election,

774
00:31:29,674 --> 00:31:31,642
and it's gonna be
the end of this

775
00:31:31,660 --> 00:31:33,744
so-called career of yours.

776
00:31:35,013 --> 00:31:36,697
You're not cut out to lead.

777
00:31:36,748 --> 00:31:38,649
You never were.

778
00:31:38,667 --> 00:31:42,169
And I may be petty or whatever
else you want to call me,

779
00:31:42,204 --> 00:31:44,488
but I'm a winner.

780
00:31:45,974 --> 00:31:48,676
And that's something
you'll never be.

781
00:31:53,365 --> 00:31:54,831
(Chuckles)

782
00:31:57,852 --> 00:31:59,687
(Gate clatters)

783
00:32:08,405 --> 00:32:10,840
Mr. President,
if I could have a word.

784
00:32:10,874 --> 00:32:13,676
You're gonna need to move
this stuff out of here, Sally.

785
00:32:13,710 --> 00:32:16,962
Of course. I'll send someone
right away.

786
00:32:18,013 --> 00:32:19,681
What do you need?

787
00:32:19,715 --> 00:32:21,365
I just wanted
to congratulate you

788
00:32:21,383 --> 00:32:22,851
on kinyazi.

789
00:32:22,902 --> 00:32:25,553
I didn't think a S.E.A.L. team
was the way to go. I was wrong.

790
00:32:25,604 --> 00:32:27,372
These things don't always
break your way.

791
00:32:27,406 --> 00:32:29,057
This time it did.

792
00:32:29,108 --> 00:32:30,825
I always wanted
to give you this.

793
00:32:32,745 --> 00:32:36,798
It's a copy of my letter
accepting your reinstatement.

794
00:32:36,832 --> 00:32:38,783
When I questioned
your readiness to serve,

795
00:32:38,818 --> 00:32:40,085
I was just thinking
about our country,

796
00:32:40,519 --> 00:32:41,602
where it would leave us,

797
00:32:41,637 --> 00:32:43,054
how it would make us look
to the world.

798
00:32:43,088 --> 00:32:46,140
I wasn't rooting for you
to fail or die.

799
00:32:46,175 --> 00:32:47,725
The truth is,
your getting shot

800
00:32:47,759 --> 00:32:50,411
was the scariest thing
that ever happened to me.

801
00:32:50,445 --> 00:32:53,331
I haven't slept a night
during this whole time.

802
00:32:56,318 --> 00:32:59,537
It is not easy
being President.

803
00:33:01,773 --> 00:33:03,590
Thank you, Sally.

804
00:33:03,624 --> 00:33:06,660
You are welcome,
Mr. President.

805
00:33:09,263 --> 00:33:10,947
Got my boy sleeping
with his phone under his pillow.

806
00:33:10,982 --> 00:33:12,883
One call from me,
this election's ours.

807
00:33:12,917 --> 00:33:15,652
- No. - We don't use him,
we're gonna lose this thing.

808
00:33:15,670 --> 00:33:17,621
Or maybe you thought that
little math girlie was wrong

809
00:33:17,655 --> 00:33:20,139
about how everything's gonna
shake out in Ohio.

810
00:33:20,190 --> 00:33:23,092
I can't <i>believe</i>
we are having this conversation.

811
00:33:23,110 --> 00:33:24,377
- Olivia, let's be practical.
- Mm.

812
00:33:24,411 --> 00:33:26,045
- What do you want?
- What?

813
00:33:26,080 --> 00:33:28,297
- What do you want out of this?
- I don't know.

814
00:33:28,331 --> 00:33:30,199
Verna here is gonna be
supreme court justice

815
00:33:30,233 --> 00:33:31,566
first time there's a vacancy.

816
00:33:31,584 --> 00:33:33,402
Cyrus is gonna be
chief of staff.

817
00:33:33,436 --> 00:33:35,254
Mellie... well, First Lady.

818
00:33:37,691 --> 00:33:39,675
And what are you, Hollis?

819
00:33:39,709 --> 00:33:41,810
I'm a guy everyone
sitting here owes a favor to.

820
00:33:41,844 --> 00:33:46,115
Olivia, you need to think
about your future and decide...

821
00:33:46,149 --> 00:33:47,783
What do you want?

822
00:33:51,287 --> 00:33:53,255
- It has to be unanimous.
- Cyrus...

823
00:33:53,289 --> 00:33:56,492
No, the only way we trust each other
is if everybody's ass is on the line.

824
00:33:56,526 --> 00:33:58,826
If it's not unanimous,
we don't do it.

825
00:33:58,827 --> 00:34:00,478
Then we don't do it.

826
00:34:01,663 --> 00:34:04,899
(Sighs)

827
00:34:07,469 --> 00:34:09,303
Governor?

828
00:34:09,338 --> 00:34:10,988
Fitz, you all right?

829
00:34:12,458 --> 00:34:15,810
My father had a heart attack
and died 20 minutes ago.

830
00:34:25,354 --> 00:34:27,505
(Projector
and camera shutter clicks)

831
00:34:33,362 --> 00:34:35,496
It was a very nice funeral.

832
00:34:39,267 --> 00:34:41,368
I liked what you said
about your father.

833
00:34:41,402 --> 00:34:43,337
It was a lie.

834
00:34:43,371 --> 00:34:46,073
The story about the dog
he got me for my 10th birthday,

835
00:34:46,107 --> 00:34:48,542
I made it up.

836
00:34:48,576 --> 00:34:50,511
'Cause you can't get up
at your father's funeral

837
00:34:50,545 --> 00:34:53,947
and tell the story about how
you sat outside his office door

838
00:34:53,982 --> 00:34:56,533
on your 10th birthday and...

839
00:34:56,568 --> 00:34:58,452
listened to him
bang his secretary.

840
00:34:58,486 --> 00:34:59,486
(Grunts)

841
00:34:59,521 --> 00:35:01,655
(Exhales)

842
00:35:03,591 --> 00:35:04,992
I'm not sad.

843
00:35:06,077 --> 00:35:07,578
I'm relieved.

844
00:35:10,582 --> 00:35:11,648
I'm free.

845
00:35:11,683 --> 00:35:13,951
(Wood clatters)
(Grunts)

846
00:35:15,203 --> 00:35:17,871
And I want it, Liv.
(Axe clatters)

847
00:35:17,906 --> 00:35:20,073
I want to win this election.

848
00:35:20,808 --> 00:35:22,809
I'm going to win.

849
00:35:24,061 --> 00:35:26,462
It's mine.

850
00:35:28,898 --> 00:35:31,183
Do you think I'll make
a good President?

851
00:35:33,503 --> 00:35:36,939
I think you'll make
a <i>great</i> President.

852
00:35:59,012 --> 00:36:00,913
Put down the axe.

853
00:36:00,947 --> 00:36:02,381
Put it down!

854
00:36:02,415 --> 00:36:03,465
(Wood clatters)

855
00:36:06,920 --> 00:36:08,737
Come here.

856
00:36:33,913 --> 00:36:36,715
(Stifled crying)

857
00:36:36,749 --> 00:36:38,600
(Sobs)

858
00:36:38,635 --> 00:36:42,154
(Sobbing)

859
00:36:42,172 --> 00:36:46,358
(Continues sobbing)

860
00:36:54,882 --> 00:36:56,449
I'm changing my locks.

861
00:36:56,483 --> 00:36:57,567
I wanted to talk to you,

862
00:36:57,601 --> 00:36:58,701
and I didn't want
to wait in the hall.

863
00:36:58,735 --> 00:37:00,369
We're done talking.
(Keys clatter)

864
00:37:00,403 --> 00:37:03,022
I've been thinking about this.
Everything.

865
00:37:03,056 --> 00:37:04,407
And you were right.

866
00:37:04,441 --> 00:37:06,109
It was sexist to suggest

867
00:37:06,143 --> 00:37:07,744
that you were in a relationship
with the President.

868
00:37:07,778 --> 00:37:10,363
I was to wrong to think
that there was a conspiracy,

869
00:37:10,397 --> 00:37:13,032
that someone forged
the President's signature.

870
00:37:13,066 --> 00:37:16,152
I'm sorry.

871
00:37:16,186 --> 00:37:17,587
I was wrong.

872
00:37:17,621 --> 00:37:21,958
You forget that
I know <i>you</i> too well.

873
00:37:21,992 --> 00:37:27,547
And so I know
when you are lying, Edison.

874
00:37:31,285 --> 00:37:33,519
I love you.

875
00:37:34,354 --> 00:37:36,355
I am <i>in</i> love with you,

876
00:37:36,406 --> 00:37:38,206
and I don't care
what you've done,

877
00:37:38,240 --> 00:37:40,242
who you've loved...
I don't care.

878
00:37:40,276 --> 00:37:42,511
And if you will have me,

879
00:37:42,545 --> 00:37:45,147
I would very much
like to marry you.

880
00:37:49,201 --> 00:37:50,985
(Groans)
You were incredible today.

881
00:37:51,020 --> 00:37:52,587
I've never seen anything
like it.

882
00:37:52,621 --> 00:37:55,323
That press conference was flawless.
(Groans)

883
00:37:55,357 --> 00:37:56,708
Struck just the right tone.

884
00:37:56,742 --> 00:38:00,127
Presidential. Strong.
Everything. Back to normal.

885
00:38:00,462 --> 00:38:02,262
(Sighs) I was worried,
I have to admit.

886
00:38:02,280 --> 00:38:04,732
I was very worried.
Something like this happens...

887
00:38:04,766 --> 00:38:06,200
a shooting or an accident...

888
00:38:06,234 --> 00:38:08,802
You remember senator Hutchins.
He was in that car accident.

889
00:38:08,837 --> 00:38:11,355
Now he's quadriplegic,
and his poor wife...

890
00:38:11,389 --> 00:38:13,207
She has to change his diapers.
(Groans softly)

891
00:38:13,241 --> 00:38:14,575
I can't even imagine.

892
00:38:14,609 --> 00:38:16,710
Your life can change in an instant.

893
00:38:16,744 --> 00:38:19,363
<i>We</i> were lucky.

894
00:38:19,397 --> 00:38:21,465
You're back. You're you.

895
00:38:21,499 --> 00:38:23,033
That is...

896
00:38:23,068 --> 00:38:26,370
To have our life go back
to the way it was...

897
00:38:26,404 --> 00:38:28,672
Is a gift.

898
00:38:28,707 --> 00:38:30,624
Everything's good.
I'm grateful.

899
00:38:30,659 --> 00:38:32,710
I'm so grateful.

900
00:38:32,744 --> 00:38:36,080
And... honestly?

901
00:38:36,114 --> 00:38:39,265
Your approval rating
has never been higher.

902
00:38:39,300 --> 00:38:41,434
You can have anything
you want right now.

903
00:38:41,452 --> 00:38:43,186
Anything.
We should think about that.

904
00:38:43,220 --> 00:38:46,439
We should take advantage
of this moment politically.

905
00:38:46,473 --> 00:38:48,675
But we have to be
smart about it.

906
00:38:48,709 --> 00:38:51,694
What do you think?
What do you want?

907
00:38:53,163 --> 00:38:56,082
If <i>you</i> could have anything...

908
00:39:01,171 --> 00:39:02,972
I want a divorce.

909
00:39:06,109 --> 00:39:07,409
You're telling me
that even though

910
00:39:07,443 --> 00:39:09,161
there are 120 million people
voting in this thing,

911
00:39:09,195 --> 00:39:10,595
all we care about is Ohio?

912
00:39:10,630 --> 00:39:11,963
Our problem isn't Ohio.

913
00:39:11,981 --> 00:39:14,416
Our problem is Franklin,
Summit, and Defiance.

914
00:39:14,450 --> 00:39:16,201
You're right.
Take out those three counties,

915
00:39:16,235 --> 00:39:18,103
and this election
is a statistical dead heat.

916
00:39:18,137 --> 00:39:19,988
It could go either way.

917
00:39:20,039 --> 00:39:21,807
Painting Reston as soft
on crime has been a godsend.

918
00:39:21,841 --> 00:39:23,859
There isn't any crime
in Defiance?

919
00:39:23,910 --> 00:39:26,094
I just do the math.
(Papers thud)

920
00:39:26,129 --> 00:39:29,347
(Telephone ringing in distance)

921
00:39:29,365 --> 00:39:31,466
I don't know how you can
even consider...

922
00:39:31,501 --> 00:39:33,819
It isn't my idea. Hollis...

923
00:39:33,853 --> 00:39:35,137
Hollis is your guy.

924
00:39:35,171 --> 00:39:37,456
Hollis is Fitz's guy.

925
00:39:37,490 --> 00:39:40,659
Let's not play innocent here.

926
00:39:41,693 --> 00:39:44,328
Fitz is clean.
Fitz walks on water.

927
00:39:44,363 --> 00:39:46,797
Fitz makes the fishes
and the loaves.

928
00:39:46,832 --> 00:39:49,016
And people like Hollis
and me and you...

929
00:39:49,067 --> 00:39:50,217
(Scoffs)

930
00:39:50,552 --> 00:39:53,071
Don't roll your eyes.

931
00:39:53,105 --> 00:39:55,940
You're one of us, Olivia.

932
00:39:55,974 --> 00:39:58,793
We march behind him.

933
00:39:59,427 --> 00:40:01,161
We sing his happy tune.

934
00:40:01,196 --> 00:40:03,030
And then we pick up
our hatchets,

935
00:40:03,081 --> 00:40:05,883
and we chop up the judases
into bloody little pieces

936
00:40:05,917 --> 00:40:10,354
and dance around their corpses,
because that is our job.

937
00:40:10,388 --> 00:40:14,575
That is what we do.
We take care of Fitz.

938
00:40:14,609 --> 00:40:17,210
And we don't do it
because we are believers,

939
00:40:17,261 --> 00:40:18,796
which we are.

940
00:40:19,630 --> 00:40:21,831
We don't do it for the rush
or the high or the power,

941
00:40:21,866 --> 00:40:23,650
which we are most
certainly junkies for.

942
00:40:23,701 --> 00:40:27,320
We do it because Fitz can't.
He can't do it.

943
00:40:27,355 --> 00:40:30,724
If he could do it, we wouldn't
worship at his altar.

944
00:40:30,758 --> 00:40:35,145
People like Fitz...
They go down in history.

945
00:40:35,179 --> 00:40:39,949
People like us, we create the history.
(Breath quavering)

946
00:40:40,767 --> 00:40:43,869
We run this world
so he can lead it.

947
00:40:43,920 --> 00:40:47,423
In order to lead it, the people
have to elect him, Cyrus.

948
00:40:47,457 --> 00:40:48,924
The people have to find him worthy.

949
00:40:48,958 --> 00:40:50,793
That's what I'm trying to tell you.

950
00:40:50,827 --> 00:40:53,479
The way this world works,

951
00:40:53,513 --> 00:40:55,765
the people is you and me

952
00:40:55,799 --> 00:40:57,867
and Hollis and Mellie and Verna.
(Breathing heavily)

953
00:40:57,901 --> 00:40:59,718
- We're the people.
- Cy...

954
00:40:59,770 --> 00:41:01,837
No. It comes down
to two questions, Olivia...

955
00:41:01,872 --> 00:41:04,573
does he deserve to be President?

956
00:41:04,608 --> 00:41:06,709
And if you believe he does,

957
00:41:06,743 --> 00:41:08,928
do you think he can win it on his own?

958
00:41:08,979 --> 00:41:12,331
If you can say "yes" to both,

959
00:41:12,382 --> 00:41:15,551
then we'll never discuss
election rigging...

960
00:41:15,569 --> 00:41:17,486
Ever again.

961
00:41:26,229 --> 00:41:28,730
Do you think I'll make
a good President?

962
00:41:28,731 --> 00:41:29,831
He's the real deal.

963
00:41:29,832 --> 00:41:32,233
- Once in a generation.
- You're gonna lose this election.

964
00:41:32,267 --> 00:41:33,651
<i>Do you think I'll make</i>
<i>a good President?</i>

965
00:41:33,685 --> 00:41:34,986
Fitzgerald can't pull this
off on his own.

966
00:41:35,037 --> 00:41:36,254
- I gotta win this election.
- What do you want?

967
00:41:36,305 --> 00:41:37,855
- It's mine.
- <i>Think about your future.</i>

968
00:41:37,890 --> 00:41:39,540
- I'm going to win...
- I'm a winner.

969
00:41:39,575 --> 00:41:41,542
- ...this election.
- That's something you'll never be.

970
00:41:41,560 --> 00:41:42,794
It's mine.

971
00:41:47,081 --> 00:41:48,900
(Cyrus) It's a finite number
of people, Mellie.

972
00:41:48,901 --> 00:41:50,251
- That's all I'm saying.
- Cyrus, we are all working

973
00:41:50,268 --> 00:41:51,368
as hard as we can work.

974
00:41:51,369 --> 00:41:52,536
I know.
I know that.

975
00:41:52,570 --> 00:41:54,020
So we tell them they just...
(Speaks indistinctly)

976
00:41:54,038 --> 00:41:55,505
Yes.

977
00:41:55,540 --> 00:41:57,274
Yes?

978
00:41:58,876 --> 00:42:00,410
So you're...

979
00:42:00,445 --> 00:42:02,329
In.

980
00:42:08,336 --> 00:42:10,870
(Beep)

981
00:42:10,888 --> 00:42:12,689
(Clears throat)

982
00:42:15,944 --> 00:42:17,561
It's a go.

